<H1><CENTER>Typical Interaction of a Chimera client (non-Applet)</CENTER></H1>

<P>This section demonstrates the interactions of various elements of Chimera's
architecture in supporting a client's access to a Chimera hyperweb.</P>

<P><TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="4" CELLPADDING="6">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="../../images/arch1.0.gif" WIDTH="575" HEIGHT="281" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><B>Step one.</B> The client contacts the Chimera server executing within
its local-area network. It <I>discovers</I> the Chimera server by locating
the server's information file in the user's home directory. This file contains
the server's hostname and port number.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="../../images/arch1.1.gif" WIDTH="575" HEIGHT="281" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><B>Step two.</B> Either the the user via the Chimera server's user-interface,
or a client via the Chimera API, specifies a URL which references a Chimera-enhanced
website. The Chimera server contacts the hyperweb manager and requests the
contact information for the site's hyperweb server.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="../../images/arch1.2.gif" WIDTH="575" HEIGHT="281" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><B>Step three.</B> Having retrieved the contact information for the hyperweb
server, the Chimera server establishes a connection to it. At this point,
the Chimera server requests a list of the hyperwebs contained on the site
from the hyperweb manager. It can then present this list to the user or
pass it back to the client.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="../../images/arch1.3.gif" WIDTH="575" HEIGHT="281" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><B>Step four.</B> Once the user or client has selected a hyperweb, the hyperweb
server loads it into memory and it is now accessible by all of the user's
clients.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

